snippet.textDisplay: Hmm, I always thought that the rate of mutation prevention/correction was yet another paramater controlled by genetics, and therefore tuned by evolution. Too much mutation = cancer, too little = evolution halts and the organism falls behinds and gets outcompeted by faster-mutating, faster-evolving cousins. So that would be the answer to the question "what's the cost of having more anti-cancer genes". How does the evidence disprove this theory, or is it one of the theories that are in the running?

snippet.textDisplay:
Is there a relationship with how susceptible organisms are to cancer and the rate of mutation and how fast it can adapt to a changing environment?
I'm wondering if a 100% cancer resistant animal just wouldn't survive for long because it doesn't mutate as much. So if the environment changes it's offspring would be less able to adapt and be natural selected.
Of course only the mutations in the sperm and egg really count so maybe that just doesn't make much sense. An animal could be 100% cancer resistant but still allow mutations to occur in their reproductive cells.

snippet.textDisplay: Longtime fan and what I like the most is that I can relate and Identify with Kurzgesagt and your subjects. 32 years old from Amsterdam, I can see I'm sharing about the same age, interests, background and free objective (holistic) worldview as you must have, (I suppose). It's really nice to see the subjects I'm interested in and wondering about are always quickly covered. Now I know getting political might be a 'hot potato' and especially when the subject might involve a delicate matter. Still, I hope and would find it brave as well as really interesting if you would be willing to let your light shine on "Totalitarianism", it's the rise in today's world in certain places and where this might possibly lead to, looking at historical facts. (Or a deeper vision on collectivism vs. 'social' individualism in the future) Just an Idea, eighter way, carry on, much love and appreciation from Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
